The paper focuses on the problem of visualizing collaborative data, which involves ratings from users on items. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, as it deals with how users interact with data. Additionally, the paper uses Bayesian networks and Markov chain Monte Carlo, which are commonly used in Information Retrieval (cs.IR) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) research. The paper also discusses metrics for evaluating the quality of visualizations, which could fall under the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with data manipulation and organization, which could fall under the Databases (cs.DB) sub-category.
